sentence: Now that we are well into earnings season and many of the big names, from tech giants such as Apple (AAPL) to more traditional companies such as P&G (PG) have reported, it is easy to lose focus on earnings.

Sooner or later these big picture issues that we keep hearing about; the price of oil, the threat of a global slowdown, widening spreads in the bond market, and of course China must become the determining factors in the course of the markets, right?
Well…not really.
All of these things have been around for a while and, until something big changes, the appropriate level of trepidation brought about by each of those threats is priced into the market.
The thing is, “risks” such as this are usually just distractions.
When something happens that really disrupts markets it is rarely something that has already been identified as a risk factor.
It is the unknown, and the shock that comes with it, that really drives movement.
Given that, then, the most fundamental of all metrics, corporate profits, should remain the focus for traders and investors for a while longer.
That should be easy enough this week, as there is something of interest each day.
Monday: Brookdale Senior Living (BKD).
BKD will report after the market closes today.
The company is going through some upheaval, with President and CFO Mark Ohlendorf transitioning to the role of President and other positions, including CFO and COO, still to be filled.
Combine that with reported losses in the last three quarters and BKD may seem like an unlikely candidate for buying into the numbers, but long term investors may wish to consider just that.
Some industries are bound to grow, often despite themselves, and senior living certainly looks that way.
There may be more trendy stocks in the space, but with a P/E just over 10 and a PEG ratio of around 0.6, there are very few with more upside than BKD.
Tuesday: Aetna (AET).
When consolidation is prevalent in an industry it is usually for one of two reasons.
Either times are bad and assets are cheap or times are good and cash is plentiful.
The M&A activity we have seen in the health insurance business recently is entirely for the second reason.
When everybody is trying to buy everybody else, though, valuations can get a little stretched, so Aetna’s results should be watched closely.
Any sign of slower than expected growth could cause ripples throughout the industry.
Wednesday: Tesla (TSLA).
No prizes for predicting what I regard as Wednesday’s most interesting earnings report!
Tesla is expected to report a loss of $1.39 per share, continuing a trend of growing losses each month.
Another one to really just grab your popcorn and watch.
At some point analysts and maybe even investors will get frustrated with dreams of the future and start looking at current results.
Will it be this quarter?
Thursday: Allergan (AGN).
There are a host of other, smaller pharmaceutical and biotech companies reporting on Thursday as well, but the most closely watched conference call will be that of Allergan.
It is doubtful that they will actually indicate where the cash from the sale of their generic business to Teva (TEVA), but every word of the report and call will be searched for clues.
That in itself could be entertaining.
Friday: JD.com (JD).
Even Friday, usually a quiet day on the earnings front, has some interest this week.
JD.com is expected to report a $0.09 loss for the quarter and any deviation from that number will be analyzed to death for clues as to the impact of stock market volatility on the Chinese consumer.
This is a situation where those with a longer perspective may find themselves hoping for a miss.
Any sign of weakness will undoubtedly put a lot of pressure on a stock which has a lot of long term potential.
JD is definitely a candidate for the “buy the dips” strategy going into the release.
Even during the height of earnings season, it is not often that every day of the week brings something that is truly of interest to everybody who watches the market.
The fact that this week does should be evidence enough that worrying about the big picture dangers to stability can be put on hold, at least for now.
